-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">paid </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">maternity cover (particularly on external grant funding) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and that funding rules make it viable to extend grants as appropriate</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increased opportunities for flexible working e.g. part-time fellowships</span></a></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Redress the gender pay gap </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Equal Pay Reviews</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Introduc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e a requirement for Universities to undertake and publish results of regular equal pay reviews to determine where to tackle gendered inequalities in pay.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Equalise maternity/paternity pay:</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">current statutory provision allows for shared maternity/paternity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">leave but on different financial terms, which acts as a deterrent/obstacle for men to play an equal part in childcare</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equalising maternity/paternity pay provisions would enable women and men to be treated equally by employers (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">i.e.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> both would be perceived </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as have potential absences for childcare rather than women being perceived as a risk, as at present) and to have equal access to career progression opportunities</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. National monitoring of:</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gender equality </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">across</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> all parts of the Research Council system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ensure elimination of any bias</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">impact of change in paternity leave entitlement, how has this translated into men and women sharing parental leave, so enabling women to re-establish working lives/achieving improved work-life balance </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Female attrition, Retention and Barriers to Careers in SET Academic Research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> UKRC 2009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘Unlocking Potential – perspectives on women in science, engineering and technology’ The Smith Institute, 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘Women, research and universities: excellence without bias’ LERU (2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://scx.sagepub.com/content/early/2013/01/24/1075547012472684.abstract"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">‘The Matilda Effect in Science Communication: An Experiment on Gender Bias in Publication Qual</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ity Perceptions and Collaboration Interest’ Science Communication (2013)</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Science faculty’s subtle gender biases favor male students</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.pnas.org/content/109/41/16474.abstract</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘The chemistry PhD: the impact on women’s retention’ Royal Society </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">for Chemistry 2009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Molecular Bioscience PhD and Women’s Retention: A Survey and Comparison with Chemistry Royal Society for Chemistry 2009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Science PhD Career preferences: Levels, Changes and Advisor encouragement. Sauermann and Roach, PLoS ONE 7:e3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">6307 (2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> www.vitae.ac.uk/wdrd</span></p></body></html>